<section>
  <div class="content">
    <header>
      <h2>What happens</h2>
    </header>
    <p>
      At first glance, this is not much of a test at all. Almost every person Brian has interviewed smiled and jumped into coding up the styles. Then when they think they're in a good spot, they refresh. And the screen is blank.
    </p>
    <p>
      Panic sets in. He can see the thoughts rush through their head: "What the heck is going on?! What did I do wrong?!"
    </p>
    <p>
      The demeanor of the interview changes. Now, Brian is testing their debugging skills. He can see how they handle stress, frustration, and pressure. They open up the browser's dev console's inspector, see what the browser picked up, and realize that their code is indeed being rendered. Then they start trying things in the dev console.
    </p>
    <p>
      Excellent! Brian can see that this person at least knows about the dev console. And they are familiar enough to use it effectively. All good signs that this person is not completely lost. They must have spent some time in web development. And now he can see the different styles that they are trying to apply. Brian is learning about the breadth of their CSS knowledge, and how far outside the box that they think. This is exactly what he wants to assess in this interview.
    </p>
    <p>
      What he really wants to see is the behavior. Do they ask questions? It's fine if they do that; it will not hurt their assessment. Do they get angry? A good interviewee will talk through their thought process; there is only so much one can glean from watching another person silently program.
    </p>
    <p>
      He has had individuals get frustrated and completely shut up. Not good.
    </p>
    <p>
      He has had individuals get angry and complain about how they would never have set up the HTML this way, and that's why they're having trouble. Maybe true, but he doesn't care. This is the challenge. To get the right answer, you don't change the question.
    </p>
    <p>
      He has had people jump over and change the HTML without asking. And reminds them that they don't need to change any of the HTML, and they inform him that it will be better this way. Ok? Good luck, I guess? "Interviewee didn't solve a single code challenge, but they did create their own challenges and solved those!"
    </p>
    <p>
      He has only ever had one person solve this without help. Brian was impressed and had to add on other requirements to fill the time. They knows who they are, and Brian hopes they read this someday.
    </p>
    <p>
      The best outcome is that they start asking questions. As they get answers, they hopefully start applying that knowledge in the right place. And once they have that knowledge, hopefully they retain it, and use it later in the exercise.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="content">
    <header>
      <h2>The Reveal</h2>
    </header>
    <p>
      He doesn't really care if they finish completely, but would like for them to get a certain amount of the way through the exercise. Brian usually finishes the challenge for them, and explains how the different pieces of the solution work, pointing out where they were close, and why it was not technically correct.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brian has had people argue with me. "[Their] solution was correct, and it would have worked fine!" He once spent 20 minutes after the interview had ended explaining to a person why his solution would have been mathematically incorrect, causing the layout to be a few fractions of a pixel out of alignment. He eventually understood the DOM parent/child relationship that was causing his % math to deteriorate. That was an attitude Brian wasn't pleased with.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brian has had people who said that it was a dumb exercise, and was completely unrealistic to most web development situations. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯
    </p>
    <p>
      And Brian has had people say, "That was totally fascinating. I didn't know about [thing], and I will never forget it now!" This is the best attitude, obviously. Brian is happy to see their excitement at learning; and their lack of ego, which allows for them to learn without resenting me.
    </p>
    <p>
      As a testament to his claim that "he doesn't really care if they finish completely", most of the people on Brian's team right now have had this interview question, and none of them finished without help. The guy that did solve it was hired, but has since moved on to other teams.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

